enough to go to medical school,

00:04:30.870 --> 00:04:33.900 align:middle line:84%
and pass the exams,
and get licensed,

00:04:33.900 --> 00:04:35.610 align:middle line:84%
they should also be
intelligent enough

00:04:35.610 --> 00:04:39.390 align:middle line:84%
to use what is a treatment
program that should work well

00:04:39.390 --> 00:04:42.200 align:middle line:90%
for the patient.

00:04:42.200 --> 00:04:46.260 align:middle line:84%
If the patient is paying
for the treatment,

00:04:46.260 --> 00:04:47.977 align:middle line:90%
they should be able to choose--

00:04:47.977 --> 00:04:50.310 align:middle line:84%
have the freedom to choose
the treatment that they think

00:04:50.310 --> 00:04:51.110 align:middle line:90%
is best for them.

00:04:51.110 --> 00:04:54.320 align:middle line:90%


00:04:54.320 --> 00:04:56.670 align:middle line:84%
In this day of
informed consent, you

00:04:56.670 --> 00:05:01.560 align:middle line:84%
must inform your patient of all
the reactions that take place,

00:05:01.560 --> 00:05:05.880 align:middle line:84%
or all about the probable
ones, so the patient

00:05:05.880 --> 00:05:08.460 align:middle line:84%
knows the pros and cons of the
treatment they're undergoing.

00:05:08.460 --> 00:05:12.188 align:middle line:84%
And if the doctor wants to
make the choice to use this,

00:05:12.188 --> 00:05:13.980 align:middle line:84%
and if the patient
wants to make the choice

00:05:13.980 --> 00:05:16.290 align:middle line:84%
to use this, why
should it not be used,

00:05:16.290 --> 00:05:18.503 align:middle line:84%
especially when it has
such a proven track record?

00:05:18.503 --> 00:05:19.920 align:middle line:84%
Things like the
Gerson therapy now

00:05:19.920 --> 00:05:24.690 align:middle line:84%
has close to a
100-year track record.

00:05:24.690 --> 00:05:27.480 align:middle line:84%
